[
    {
        "step": 1,
        "concept": "Precision and Recall",
        "description": "Solidify the understanding of precision and recall, derived from the confusion matrix. Learn that precision measures the accuracy of positive alerts (how many flagged items are truly defective), while recall measures the ability to find all defective items. A model collision to test understanding: A model that flags every single code commit as 'risky' will have perfect recall (1.0) but very poor precision. Is this a useful model for deployment? Why or why not?",
        "resources": ["Precision and Recall - Wikipedia", "Machine Learning Mastery: Precision and Recall for Classification"]
    },
    {
        "step": 2,
        "concept": "The Decision Threshold",
        "description": "Understand that a classifier's output is often a probability score between 0 and 1. The decision threshold (e.g., 0.5) is the cut-off point above which a prediction is classified as 'risky' (positive). Learn how shifting this threshold directly changes the number of false positives and false negatives. A model collision: If you set the threshold to 0.0, what happens to your confusion matrix? What about at 1.0? This illustrates the precision-recall trade-off controlled by the threshold.",
        "resources": ["Scikit-learn documentation: predict_proba", "Towards Data Science: Understanding Thresholds in Classification"]
    },
    {
        "step": 3,
        "concept": "Threshold Tuning & Trade-offs",
        "description": "Learn that there is no single 'correct' threshold; it is a business decision based on the cost of false positives (wasting time reviewing safe code) versus false negatives (missing a critical defect). Explore how to visualize this trade-off using a Precision-Recall curve. A model collision: In a safety-critical system, you might prioritize recall to catch all defects, accepting more false positives. For a low-stakes, high-volume system, you might prioritize precision to avoid alert fatigue. What happens to the other metric in each case?",
        "resources": ["Precision-Recall Curve tutorial", "Article: The Trade-off Between Precision and Recall"]
    },
    {
        "step": 4,
        "concept": "Optimization Metrics (F1, F-beta)",
        "description": "Learn about metrics that combine precision and recall into a single score to help compare models or select a threshold. The F1 score is the harmonic mean, balancing the two equally. The F-beta score allows you to weight recall (beta > 1) or precision (beta < 1) as more important. A model collision: Optimizing purely for F1 score might select a threshold that is suboptimal if the costs of false positives and false negatives are not symmetrical. Why would a simple average of precision and recall be a poor choice compared to a harmonic mean?",
        "resources": ["F1 Score and F-beta Score Explained", "Scikit-learn: f1_score and fbeta_score functions"]
    },
    {
        "step": 5,
        "concept": "Deployment-Centric Tuning Strategies",
        "description": "Move from theory to practical strategies for setting the threshold in a deployment context. Learn to define operational constraints (e.g., 'we can only review 10 alerts per day' sets a limit on false positives) and tune the threshold to meet them. Explore methods like setting a threshold to achieve a desired recall or precision value. A model collision: You tune a threshold to achieve 95% precision on your test set. When deployed, the precision drops to 70%. What could be the reasons? (Hint: concept drift, data distribution differences). This highlights that threshold tuning is not a one-time task.",
        "resources": ["Practical Guide to Threshold Tuning for Business", "Monitoring Machine Learning Models in Production"]
    }
]

